<refentry xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:db="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" version="5.0-subset Scilab" xml:lang="en" xml:id="macglov">
  <info>
    <pubdate>$LastChangedDate$</pubdate>
  </info>
  <refnamediv>
    <refname>macglov</refname>
    <refpurpose> Mac Farlane Glover problem</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>
  <refsynopsisdiv>
    <title>Calling Sequence</title>
    <synopsis>[P,r]=macglov(Sl)</synopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>
  <refsection>
    <title>Parameters</title>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Sl</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>linear system (<literal>syslin</literal> list)</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>P</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>linear system (<literal>syslin</literal> list), ``augmented'' plant</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>r</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>1x2 vector, dimension of <literal>P22</literal></para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </refsection>
  <refsection>
    <title>Description</title>
    <para><literal>[P,r]=macglov(Sl)</literal> returns the standard plant
    <literal>P</literal> for the Glover-McFarlane problem.</para>
    <para>
    For this problem ro_optimal = 1-hankel_norm(<literal>[N,M]</literal>)
    with <literal>[N,M]=lcf(sl)</literal> (Normalized coprime factorization) i.e.</para>
    <para>
    gama_optimal = <literal>1/sqrt(ro_optimal)</literal></para>
  </refsection>
  <refsection>
    <title>Authors</title>
    <para>F. Delebecque INRIA</para>
  </refsection>
</refentry>
